<A name=The_32bit_6502_exists></A><A name=The32bit6502exists></A><span class=moyet>==</span><span class=blogtitle><b>The 32-bit 6502 exists</b></span><span class=moyet>==</span>

<p>

I always wanted to see a 32-bit or 64-bit 6502 with protected mode. Well, it exists. It’s called the ARM—the principal architects of the ARM were hardcore 6502 programmers and the ARM has 6502 quirks like rotate instructions that use the carry bit and “bne” (same mnemonic as the 6502) meaning “branch if not zero”.

<p>

<blockquote>
<A href="http://www.ot1.com/arm/armchap1.html">http:/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>www.<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>ot<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>1.<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>com/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>arm/<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>armchap<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>1.<![if gt IE 6]>&#8203;<![endif]><wbr>html</A>
</blockquote>

It looks like the ARM architecture is slowly replacing the x86, which I think is a good thing.

